rComments: This course is bittersweet. Prof Hayter is an amazing prof, engaging lecturer, fair grader and gets to know all of her students on a personal level. That being said, her course load is VERY heavy. BUT get ready to spend HOURS each week reading and writing summaries in addition to group work, essays, midterms, a final and a seminar presentations.

Willing to help if you put the effort in, very flexible even though she expects a lot of hard work from her students. Seems like she genuinely wants us to learn something from the class, even though it's a seminar.
teacherRatingTags: ['Get ready to read', 'Accessible outside class', 'So many papers']

rComments: This class is structured like a seminar, however the prof BARELY lectures or structures the class discussion. LOTS of assignments worth very few marks (5-10%). Extremely rude to students if you don't know exactly what you're talking about. LOTS of really dry and really old readings, some which are very inaccessible.

Came into my class mid-semester to cover for my prof. When you first meet her, she seems very nice, but she likes to belittle students and make them feel bad. Has a very sassy tone when she talks to students. She expects you to do the readings and participate a lot in class.

This chick has major issues with men. She has a million ex-boyfriends that she has yet to get over and tells the class about it. Psycho red head - don't be late for class or she'll lock you out. Controlling and hard assignments worth 10%. Be afraid; be very afraid.

Long/numerous assignments each worth about 10%, inappropriately speaks of her ex-boyfriends in class (clearly wants to demonstrate that she has major issues with men) and not professional. Although the grading is not difficult, class isn't worth taking with her.
Brings experience from outside the University to the    required material.  Very interactive classes.  Long assignments.

weak on theory, heavy on self promotion and 'industry' insights...not a 4th year calibre, more like a professional development seminar. not horrible, but can be tedious...beware of her self-defensive streak and managerial superciliousness.
Brutally long assignments, but nice lady in general.
no-nonsense attitude; likes interactive class participation; working with her business-like approach to teaching is key to enjoying her class.
